<emphasis bold="true" box="[681,951,1600,1630]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
The 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dunn" baseAuthorityYear="1947" box="[745,857,1600,1630]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pavonis">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[745,857,1600,1630]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">pavonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[96,1536,1675,2005]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Dunn first used the Latin word for &quot;peacock&quot; (
<emphasis box="[760,824,1675,1705]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">pavo</emphasis>
) when he described 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dunn" baseAuthorityYear="1947" box="[1126,1272,1675,1705]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pavonis">
<emphasis box="[1126,1272,1675,1705]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. pavonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 1947. He later wrote an account of the display of this spider in a now-defunct Australian magazine, 
<emphasis box="[1293,1439,1712,1742]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Walkabout</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dunn" firstAuthor="Dunn" journalOrPublisher="Walkabout" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="38 - 39" refId="ref8664" refString="Dunn, R. A. 1957. The Peacock Spider. Walkabout, April 1 st, 1957: 38 - 39." title="The Peacock Spider" type="book chapter" year="1957">Dunn 1957</bibRefCitation>
). At the time, only two species in this group were known, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dunn" baseAuthorityYear="1947" box="[963,1104,1750,1780]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pavonis">
<emphasis box="[963,1104,1750,1780]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. pavonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rainbow" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[1170,1339,1750,1780]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis box="[1170,1339,1750,1780]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Males within this group can often be identified by the presence of a large red circle or &quot;target&quot; on the fan, but this is often obscured or replaced by a covering of light brown scales. Some males do not even raise their fan as they display. Spiders of Western Australia presently identified as either 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dunn" baseAuthorityYear="1947" box="[1156,1304,1862,1892]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pavonis">
<emphasis box="[1156,1304,1862,1892]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. pavonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="pavonis" variety="brunneis">
<emphasis box="[1325,1473,1862,1892]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. pavonis</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[96,213,1900,1930]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">brunneis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baehr &amp; Whyte" authorityYear="2016" box="[268,600,1900,1930]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="pavonis" variety="nornalup">
<emphasis box="[268,411,1900,1930]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. pavonis</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[477,600,1900,1930]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">nornalup</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Otto &amp; Hill" box="[618,864,1901,1931]" firstAuthor="Otto" journalOrPublisher="Peckhamia" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 81" part="103" refId="ref9875" refString="Otto, J. C. and D. E. Hill. 2012 c. Notes on Maratus Karsch 1878 and related jumping spiders from Australia, with five new species (Araneae: Salticidae: Euophryinae). Peckhamia 103. 1: 1 - 81." title="Notes on Maratus Karsch 1878 and related jumping spiders from Australia, with five new species (Araneae: Salticidae: Euophryinae)" type="journal article" year="2012" yearSuffix="c">
Otto &amp; Hill 2012 
<bibRefCitation author="Otto, J. C. &amp; D. E. Hill" box="[850,968,1902,1931]" firstAuthor="c" journalOrPublisher="Peckhamia" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 82" part="103" refId="ref9968" refString="Otto, J. C. and D. E. Hill. 2012 e. Notes on Maratus Karsch 1878 and related jumping spiders from Australia, with five new species (Araneae: Salticidae: Euophryinae), version 2. Peckhamia 103. 2: 1 - 82." title="Notes on Maratus Karsch 1878 and related jumping spiders from Australia, with five new species (Araneae: Salticidae: Euophryinae), version 2" type="journal article" year="2012" yearSuffix="e">c, 2012e</bibRefCitation>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Baehr &amp; Whyte" box="[982,1275,1901,1931]" firstAuthor="Baehr" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="501 - 525" part="4154" refId="ref8468" refString="Baehr, B. C. and R. Whyte. 2016. The peacock spiders (Araneae: Salticidae: Maratus) of the Queensland Museum, including six new species. Zootaxa 4154 (5): 501 - 525." title="The peacock spiders (Araneae: Salticidae: Maratus) of the Queensland Museum, including six new species" type="journal article" year="2016">Baehr &amp; Whyte 2016</bibRefCitation>
) are included here with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dunn" baseAuthorityYear="1947" box="[169,312,1937,1967]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pavonis">
<emphasis box="[169,312,1937,1967]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. pavonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but need further study. Unlike the eastern 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dunn" baseAuthorityYear="1947" box="[927,1070,1937,1967]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pavonis">
<emphasis box="[927,1070,1937,1967]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. pavonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the fan of these western spiders may have large lateral flaps or more light-brown scale cover, and the legs may have fewer markings.
</paragraph>
